## Documentation
#
# standard colors
#
# Below are the color init strings for the basic file types. A color init
# string consists of one or more of the following numeric codes:
# Attribute codes:
# 00=none 01=bold 04=underscore 05=blink 07=reverse 08=concealed
# Text color codes:
# 30=black 31=red 32=green 33=yellow 34=blue 35=magenta 36=cyan 37=white
# Background color codes:
# 40=black 41=red 42=green 43=yellow 44=blue 45=magenta 46=cyan 47=white
#
#
# 256 color support
# see here: http://www.mail-archive.com/bug-coreutils@gnu.org/msg11030.html)
#
# Text 256 color coding:
# 38;5;COLOR_NUMBER
# Background 256 color coding:
# 48;5;COLOR_NUMBER

## Special files

NORMAL 00;38;5;7 # normal file: light gray
#FILE 00 # regular file: use no color at all
RESET 0 # reset to "normal" color
DIR 00;38;5;4 # directory: blue (7aa2f7)
LINK 01;38;5;6 # symbolic link: bright cyan (7dcfff)
MULTIHARDLINK 00 # regular file with more than one link
FIFO 48;5;8;38;5;3;01 # pipe: dark bg + yellow text
SOCK 48;5;8;38;5;16;01 # socket: dark bg + orange text
DOOR 48;5;8;38;5;16;01 # door: dark bg + orange text
BLK 48;5;8;38;5;12;01 # block device driver: dark bg + bright blue
CHR 48;5;8;38;5;12;01 # character device driver: dark bg + bright blue
ORPHAN 48;5;8;38;5;9 # symlink to nonexistent file: dark bg + bright red
SETUID 48;5;17;38;5;15 # file that is setuid: red bg + bright white
SETGID 48;5;16;38;5;15 # file that is setgid: orange bg + bright white
CAPABILITY 30;41 # file with capability: standard
STICKY_OTHER_WRITABLE 48;5;2;38;5;0 # dir sticky + other-writable: green bg + black
OTHER_WRITABLE 48;5;8;38;5;2 # dir other-writable: dark bg + green
STICKY 48;5;4;38;5;15 # dir sticky: blue bg + bright white
# This is for files with execute permission:
EXEC 01;38;5;2 # executable: bright green (9ece6a)

